5/5 💡 Save energy: Turn off lights and electronics when not in use, unplug chargers, and switch to energy-efficient appliances. Small changes in your energy consumption can have a big impact on your carbon footprint. #energyefficiency

4/5 ♻️ Reduce, reuse, recycle: Minimize waste by opting for reusable products, repairing items instead of replacing them, and recycling properly. Be conscious of your consumption habits and aim for a zero-waste lifestyle. #ZeroWaste

3/5 🥦 Eat a plant-based diet: Animal agriculture contributes significantly to greenhouse gas emissions. By reducing your meat and dairy consumption, you can help lower your carbon footprint. #plantbased

2/5 🚲 Opt for greener transportation: Walk, bike, or take public transport whenever possible. If you must drive, consider carpooling or switching to an electric or hybrid vehicle. #GreenTransportation

She received the 2020 Dr. A.H. Heineken Prize for Environmental Sciences and other awards for her contributions to science.

two independent committees that advise their respective Governments on responding to climate change. She was appointed Commander of the Order of the British Empire (CBE) in 2019 for services to climate change science.

She is author of the 3rd, 4th and 5th Assessments of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC). Chairs the French Haut conseil pour le climat and is member of the UK Committee on Climate Change,

Corinne formerly led the annual update of the Global Carbon Budget, an international effort of the Global Carbon Project to provide the latest information on global and national carbon emissions and their partitioning among the atmosphere, land and oceans, including their drivers
She also instigated and led for 13 years the annual update of the ’global carbon budget’, an international effort to keep track of global carbon emissions and their fate in the environment.

Her original approaches are helping to determine how and why the natural carbon reservoirs are changing, particularly in the Southern Ocean. She led the way in making marine carbon-cycle models with new ways to show the diversity and ecology of plankton.

Her wide-ranging interests have led her to work in areas like sustainable development, the detection and attribution of ocean oxygen trends to climate change, and the economic benefits of reducing uncertainty in carbon emissions and sinks.

She looks at both emissions from fossil fuel burning and those from land-use changes, the partitioning of these emissions among the atmosphere, land, and oceans, and the economic and social drivers of recent trends.
Corinne also studies the human and natural drivers of carbon emissions, as well as the science of emissions verification using Earth System Data.

Corinne’s research mainly focuses on the interactions between the carbon cycle and climate change in the atmosphere and oceans, and despite all her qualifications and awards, she’s the first to admit that she doesn’t know everything.

She is a physicist specialised in understanding the carbon cycle and how it interacts with the Earth’s climate. Corinne is ranked as one of the most influential scientists in the world studying the climate and is one of only a handful of women.
